If I ran the crypto enforcement unit at the US Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission, and I were as crypto-skeptical as the actual SEC seems to be, I gue=
ss I would want my cases to divide roughly evenly into two categories:
=09Important cases against big crypto projects and, especially, crypto exch=
anges, cases that will set important precedents and have large impact on th=
e crypto industry.   Enforcement actions against=C2=A0exchanges, in particu=
lar, are likely to have huge effects: If you shut down crypto=C2=A0trading=
=C2=A0at centralized exchanges, you get a lot more consumer-protection bang=
 for your buck than if you have to shut down every questionable crypto proj=
ect individually.=09Dumb easy cases against wild scams.

Category 2 is important for a couple of reasons. For one thing, those cases=
 are fun for the lawyers. Also you=E2=80=99ll probably win. Also people=C2=
=A0do=C2=A0seem to lose a lot of money to wild crypto scams, and it=E2=80=
=99s nice to get some back for them.
For another thing, those cases=C2=A0do=C2=A0set good precedents: If you bri=
ng a securities fraud case against an absolutely wild scam, the scammers wi=
ll probably say =E2=80=9Cno no no, we were not doing=C2=A0securities fraud,=
 because our scam tokens were not=C2=A0securities.=E2=80=9D But that argume=
nt won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0go over well with a judge, who will be inclined to sa=
y =E2=80=9Cah come on, you were doing a scam, I=E2=80=99m not gonna let you=
 off on a technicality=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so the judge will be mor=
e likely to rule that the tokens were securities.=C2=A0It is perhaps not a =
coincidence that we have discussed two big crypto cases that are going on i=
n New York federal courts right now, one against Ripple Labs Inc., which so=
ld investors tokens that are down a modest 66% from their 2021 peak, and th=
e other against Terraform Labs Pte, which sold investors tokens that are do=
wn a dreadful 99.9999% since their 2022 peak, and whose founder is  in jail=
 in Montenegro.
  [1]
=C2=A0Both Ripple and Terra have argued that their tokens are not securitie=
s; Ripple=E2=80=99s argument on that point   has mostly succeeded, while   =
Terra=E2=80=99s has failed. Ripple may or may not have a better=C2=A0legal=
=C2=A0argument, but it definitely has a better=C2=A0look=C2=A0than Terra.
Also, just, the more hilarious crypto frauds the SEC can sue, the better is=
 its broad argument,=C2=A0to courts and legislators and the public, that =
=E2=80=9Ccome on, someone needs to regulate crypto, and nobody else is doin=
g it, so you might as well let us.=E2=80=9D If the SEC finds one ludicrous =
fraud a week in the crypto space, it is harder to argue that the SEC should=
 just leave crypto alone.
Anyway here=E2=80=99s a dumb crypto enforcement case from the SEC against a=
 barely crypto thing called=C2=A0HyperFund:

The Securities and Exchange Commission today charged Xue Lee (aka Sam Lee) =
and Brenda Chunga (aka Bitcoin Beautee) for their involvement in a fraudule=
nt crypto asset pyramid scheme known as HyperFund that raised more than $1.=
7 billion from investors worldwide.
According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, from June 2020 through early 2022=
, Lee and Chunga promoted HyperFund =E2=80=9Cmembership=E2=80=9D packages, =
which they claimed guaranteed investors high returns, including from HyperF=
und=E2=80=99s supposed crypto asset mining operations and associations with=
 a Fortune 500 company. As the complaint alleges, however, Lee and Chunga k=
new or were reckless in not knowing that HyperFund was a pyramid scheme and=
 had no real source of revenue other than funds received from investors. In=
 2022, the HyperFund scheme collapsed and investors were no longer able to =
make withdrawals.

From  the complaint this case does seem like one that was just fun for the =
lawyers:

One of the details Chunga touted was the fact that Lee and another one of t=
he Founders were featured and interviewed in an episode of an Amazon Prime =
documentary series called =E2=80=9CNext: Blockchain.=E2=80=9D
In one presentation, Chunga leveraged HyperFund=E2=80=99s Founders=E2=80=99=
 public-facing profiles in order to persuade investors that there was no ri=
sk in investing with the HyperTech Group: =E2=80=9CSome people say things, =
how do we know they won=E2=80=99t just take our money and disappear? Well, =
ladies and gents, they have more to lose than to gain. They=E2=80=99re all =
over CNN. They have publicly traded companies, they are on Amazon Prime, th=
eir faces are everywhere. They have more to lose than to gain.=E2=80=9D

There was a pivot to the metaverse:
In the fall of 2021, HyperFund rebranded itself as HyperVerse. HyperVerse w=
as officially launched on December 5, 2021. Part of the new HyperVerse narr=
ative was that the HyperTech Group was creating a virtual world to connect =
people in the HyperVerse Ecosystem, which you would enter using your virtua=
l avatar.
Speaking of virtual avatars, apparently its CEO was fake?
During this launch event, which took place live online and was recorded and=
 then made available publicly online, HyperVerse presented a new supposed C=
EO of HyperVerse,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CSteven Reece Lewis.=E2=80=9D In a recorded =
video played during the launch event, Lewis thanked everyone for their part=
icipation and for giving him =E2=80=9Cthe chance to share more about HyperV=
erse, our operations, and future direction . . . . =E2=80=9D After repeated=
ly invoking a prominent social media company=E2=80=99s rebranding, =E2=80=
=9CCEO Lewis=E2=80=9D explained that HyperVerse offered a =E2=80=9Cvirtual =
world=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9Cnew business opportunities=E2=80=9D and the de=
velopment of a crypto asset, characterized as a =E2=80=9Cnative token,=E2=
=80=9D called =E2=80=9CHVT.=E2=80=9D In reality, the person presented as Le=
wis was an actor playing a role of a fabricated character. He was not the C=
EO of HyperVerse.
There is very little discussion of Hyperfund=E2=80=99s technology or token =
economics, and I=E2=80=99m not sure it had any. Its technology was telling =
people that if they invested money in its business, it would give them way =
more money in return. That=C2=A0does=C2=A0sound like a securities offering,=
 doesn=E2=80=99t it?

