   =20
      Art valuation
   =20
 =20

We have   talked a few times about the long-running dispute between art dea=
ler Yves Bouvier and his former customer Dmitry Rybolovlev. Basically Bouvi=
er would buy a painting for $126 million, tell Rybolovlev =E2=80=9CI think =
I can get this painting for you for $185 million, the sellers want $190 mil=
lion but I=E2=80=99ll try to talk them down,=E2=80=9D and then he=E2=80=99d=
 sell Rybolovlev the painting for $184 million. Rybolovlev thought he got a=
 good deal and good service from Bouvier, who was able to talk the sellers =
down from their asking price. But really he got a bad deal and bad service =
from Bouvier, who=C2=A0was=C2=A0the seller, and who took only a little bit =
off his own enormous undisclosed markup.
The question is basically, was Bouvier allowed to do this (as a third-party=
 seller in a sharp-elbowed market), or not (as a trusted advisor in a fiduc=
iary relationship with Rybolovlev). Courts in various countries have mostly=
 said it=E2=80=99s fine, but there=E2=80=99s a trial on in New York now in =
which Rybolovlev is suing Sotheby=E2=80=99s, the auction house, for helping=
 Bouvier inflate his valuations.
For some reason this is a thing? Like, Bouvier would buy a painting at a mo=
re-or-less made-up number from someone else, and then he=E2=80=99d make up =
a higher number to tell Rybolovlev, and then Rybolovlev would pay that high=
er number or something close to it. But before doing so, I suppose he neede=
d some independent third party to say =E2=80=9Coh yes, that number, that=E2=
=80=99s a good number.=E2=80=9D None of this is real, there are no cash flo=
ws, each item is unique and there is no fungible liquid market for it, and =
the correct value for a=C2=A0da Vinci painting=C2=A0is surely =E2=80=9Cwhat=
ever the most enthusiastic Russian oligarch or Saudi prince will pay for it=
.=E2=80=9D Any valuation that anyone gave Rybolovlev was necessarily self-r=
eferential.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s a fun  Financial Times article about how that case is going:
Over multiple days of testimony, Samuel Valette =E2=80=94 the global head o=
f private sales at Sotheby=E2=80=99s who sold many of the works to Bouvier,=
 the Swiss dealer who worked for years with Rybolovlev =E2=80=94 detailed t=
he process by which works, including Leonardo da Vinci=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CS=
alvator Mundi=E2=80=9D, were procured for Bouvier, his top client at the ti=
me.
Salvator Mundi=E2=80=99s modern price history is:
=09A group of art dealers  paid $1,175 for it=C2=A0in 2005 at an auction in=
 New Orleans. They had it restored, and people became convinced it was the =
original by da Vinci.=09In 2013, Sotheby=E2=80=99s negotiated a sale betwee=
n those dealers and Bouvier, =E2=80=9Cwho started negotiations with what he=
 described as a =E2=80=98brutally low=E2=80=99 offer of about $47mn. The se=
llers were hoping for at least $100mn.=E2=80=9D Ultimately Bouvier paid =E2=
=80=9C$68mn, plus a painting by Picasso valued at $12mn,=E2=80=9D which I g=
uess adds up to $80 million if you believe the number on the Picasso.=09=E2=
=80=9CBouvier would sell the painting to Rybolovlev shortly afterwards for =
$127.5mn.=E2=80=9D=09=E2=80=9CFour years later, Rybolovlev resold the work =
at auction, this time at Christie=E2=80=99s, for a record-shattering $450mn=
,=E2=80=9D  apparently to Abu Dhabi.

So the reasonable range of possible values of this painting would run from,=
 say, $1,000 to $450 million. Just, really, pick a number. And Sotheby=E2=
=80=99s did:

Emails show how as art valuations soared, margins of $5mn to $10mn on these=
 =E2=80=9Ctrophy=E2=80=9D artworks felt like rounding errors. Over email in=
 2015, Valette expressed frustration when a colleague at Sotheby=E2=80=99s =
pushed back on his request for a higher valuation for the da Vinci painting=
 two years after the original sale to Bouvier was agreed. The colleague sai=
d =E2=82=AC95mn was =E2=80=9Cthe most [he] could live with=E2=80=9D but Val=
ette told the court he thought =E2=80=9C95 was too precise=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Can awkward number=E2=80=9D, and pushed for =E2=82=AC100mn, or about $=
110mn.
Valette said he wanted a big, round number. =E2=80=9CIn this world, if you=
=E2=80=99re at =E2=82=AC95mn, you=E2=80=99re at =E2=82=AC100mn, =E2=80=9D h=
e said.

I=E2=80=99m sorry, that=E2=80=99s just correct, if you are providing a valu=
ation of that painting to a potential buyer, the correct valuation is just =
a piece of paper saying =E2=80=9Chow frisky are you feeling?=E2=80=9D Too m=
uch precision really is awkward.

