   =20
      Pivot to AI
   =20
 =20

Sure   whatever:

Advertising giant Publicis Groupe SA made an unusual executive hire in mid-=
2022 =E2=80=93 a lion-headed digital avatar named Leon who would serve as =
=E2=80=9Cchief metaverse officer,=E2=80=9D guiding clients through the virt=
ual realm that had seized real-world attention.
His moment in the spotlight didn=E2=80=99t last long.
Five months later, ChatGPT debuted, and the buzz that had surrounded the me=
taverse ever since Mark Zuckerberg rebranded Facebook as Meta Platforms Inc=
. shifted to artificial intelligence. Leon and other, human officers focuse=
d on the metaverse =E2=80=94 an immersive digital reality where people can =
interact with one another =E2=80=94 quickly became an endangered species. =
=E2=80=A6
Instead, businesses are scrambling to appoint AI leaders, with Accenture an=
d GE HealthCare making recent hires. A few metaverse executives have even r=
einvented themselves as AI experts, deftly switching from one hot technolog=
y to the next. Compensation packages average well above $1 million, accordi=
ng to a survey from executive-search and leadership advisory firm Heidrick =
& Struggles. Last week, Publicis said it would invest 300 million euros ($3=
27 million) over the next three years on artificial intelligence technology=
 and talent.

I mean, if your chief metaverse officer was an imaginary digital lion, (1) =
firing him is fine, he won=E2=80=99t be upset, he doesn=E2=80=99t need this=
 job to feed his virtual cubs,=C2=A0and (2) surely your new chief artificia=
l intelligence officer should be a chatbot? It is truly incredible how inte=
nse and how brief the whole =E2=80=9Cmetaverse=E2=80=9D thing was:

=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s been a long time since I have had a conversation with=
 a client about the metaverse,=E2=80=9D said Fawad Bajwa, the global AI pra=
ctice leader at the Russell Reynolds Associates executive search and adviso=
ry firm. =E2=80=9CThe metaverse might still be there, but it=E2=80=99s a lo=
nely place.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
Most companies have largely moved on from the metaverse. The word was utter=
ed just twice on earnings calls at S&P 500 businesses last quarter, compare=
d with 63 times in 2022=E2=80=99s first quarter, according to Bloomberg tra=
nscript data. That year, eight out of ten CEOs said they were either hiring=
 dedicated talent with expertise in the space or expanding the responsibili=
ties of their leadership teams to cover it, according to Russell Reynolds. =
All were chasing a piece of a global business opportunity that McKinsey & C=
o. consultants at the time optimistically estimated could be worth $5 trill=
ion by 2030.

You could imagine three skill sets here:
=09Metaverse skills: I don=E2=80=99t know, designing digital lion avatars o=
r whatever.=09AI skills: understanding how modern artificial intelligence m=
odels work, how to build them, how to deploy and use them, etc.=09Internal =
politics and entrepreneurship: understanding that saying =E2=80=9Cmetaverse=
=E2=80=9D would get you a big job and budget and bonus in 2022, but saying =
=E2=80=9CAI=E2=80=9D will get you those things in 2024. What magic word wil=
l get you those things in 2026? Probably somebody will know before I do.

My assumption is that Skill 1 was valuable in 2022 and Skill 2 is valuable =
in 2024, though I can=E2=80=99t be sure; I have no particular evidence that=
 the chief metaverse officers hired in 2022 were in fact any good at doing =
metaverse stuff. (Was the lion?) And my assumption is that Skill 3 is sort =
of permanently valuable, perhaps more so the more trends and technologies c=
hange.=C2=A0

