   =20
      Pricing
   =20
 =20

I don=E2=80=99t know, this is just a useful thing to learn at a young age:
He broke into the city=E2=80=99s private-school set and soon found himself =
in the fancy Fifth Avenue apartment of a new client. Rim says that one day =
this teen=E2=80=99s mother gave him a reality check. As Rim recalls it, =E2=
=80=9CShe said, =E2=80=98Chris, if you want to make it here in New York, yo=
u cannot charge $75. No one=E2=80=99s going to take you seriously.=E2=80=99=
 =E2=80=9D Rim says she told him to charge $1,500 an hour and vowed to brin=
g him more clients.
That=E2=80=99s from this New York Magazine story about Christopher Rim, the=
 founder of Command Education, an extremely expensive college admissions co=
unseling service. As a young man out of Yale, he started a modestly priced =
college admissions counseling service, until a client correctly told him th=
at there was more demand for an extremely expensive one.
We=E2=80=99ve   talked about Rim before, when   Bloomberg News reported tha=
t another parent gave him another great pricing idea: =E2=80=9CRim said a p=
arent at New York=E2=80=99s Trinity School =E2=80=94 a $64,000-a-year Ivy L=
eague-feeder =E2=80=94 once offered him $1.5 million if he would agree not =
to work with any of his child=E2=80=99s classmates.=E2=80=9D Basically if y=
ou are extremely rich, and buying positional goods like good college resume=
s, it is to your benefit for those goods to be as expensive =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and thus exclusive =E2=80=94 as possible. If you are in the business of sel=
ling those goods, that=E2=80=99s nice for you.

