<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Auditor independence</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The business of public company auditing has at=
 its heart a conflict of interest:=C2=A0</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your job, as an auditor, is to scruti=
nize a company=E2=80=99s financial statements and make sure that they are t=
rue and accurate, and then to certify those statements to the public. If th=
e company is doing financial fraud, you should try not to certify their fin=
ancial statements. If you sign off on the financial statements of a big fra=
ud, you will look bad and maybe <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQXJ0a=
HVyX0FuZGVyc2Vu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6cc8ab5b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=09get in troubl=
e</a>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company=C2=A0<em>gives=
=C2=A0</em>you that job. It hires you, in a reasonably competitive market. =
If you are annoying to work with, or are difficult about signing off on thi=
ngs, then it might hire someone else. If you are pleasant and friendly and =
take the company=E2=80=99s chief financial officer out to nice dinners, she=
 will be more likely to retain you.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are friends with your clients you will =
keep more clients. But if you are friends with your clients you might not b=
e a strict independent auditor of their financial statements.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is hard to get=C2=A0<em>rid=C2=A0</em>of th=
is conflict of interest, though people sometimes suggest ideas. (If you <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34176316.282398/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cubmJlci5vcmcvcGFwZXJzL3czMDY0NA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf6cc41d9=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> assign auditors to companies randomly</a>, they=E2=80=99d presum=
ably be more independent? If <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly9hYm1hZ2F6aW5lLmFjY2FnbG9iYWwuY29tL2ds=
b2JhbC9hcnRpY2xlcy8yMDIyL25vdi9hY2NhL2F1ZGl0b3Itc2hvdWxkLWJlLWhpcmVkLWJ5LXN=
oYXJlaG9sZGVyLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e96daeb" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> shareholde=
rs paid them</a>, instead of management, that might help?) But there are tw=
o main ways to mitigate it by regulation. The more important way is that yo=
u just have professional standards of quality and ethics for auditors, and =
you train the auditors in these standards, and then hopefully the auditors =
will do a good audit even if they are friendly with their clients. =E2=80=
=9CSorry, I know we just went out to a nice dinner last night, but I found =
some errors in your financials and my duty as an auditor outweighs our frie=
ndly relationship,=E2=80=9D the auditor maybe says, or at least she worries=
 that if she signs off on a bad audit she will get in trouble.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other way, though, is that regulation proh=
ibits=C2=A0<em>some </em>conflicts of interest that make auditors less inde=
pendent. Usually not the most important one =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the company=
=E2=80=99s managers=C2=A0hire=C2=A0and work with the auditor who sign=C2=A0=
off on their financials =E2=80=94=C2=A0because that is central to the whole=
 business. (Though=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMDMveW91ci1hdWRpdG9yLWlzLW5vdC15b3VyLWZyaWVuZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQw=
MTMwMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ=
1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBe2b2ef0b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">we talked a few years ago</a> about an auditor who got=
 in trouble for too blatantly using his friendship with a company=E2=80=99s=
 chief accounting officer to win that company=E2=80=99s auditing business.)=
 But usually regulation restricts other conflicts that are easier to identi=
fy. Auditing firms tend to also have consulting businesses, and it used to =
be standard practice for them to cross-sell consulting services to audit cl=
ients, but that is now <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbmRlcnNvbi1yZXZpZXcudWNsYS5lZHUvc2VwYXJhdG=
luZy1hdWRpdGluZy1mcm9tLWNvbnN1bHRpbmctbW9yZS1jb21wbGV4LXRoYW4taXQtc2VlbXMv/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd50e3b8a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> mostly forbidden</a> in the US.=
 And we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34176316.2=
82398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTQtMDUtM=
jAvYWNjb3VudGFudC1iZXQtY2xpZW50LXMtbW9uZXktYXQtY2xpZW50LXMtY2FzaW5vP2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDAxMzAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDEzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBe404c5fd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked once</a> about a guy who =E2=80=9Cre=
peatedly accepted tens of thousands of dollars in casino markers=E2=80=9D f=
rom a casino he was auditing, which I suppose compromised his independence.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rules get nitpicky enough that the big aud=
it firms just have to do occasional mass apologies for violating them const=
antly? <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34176316.28=
2398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYTNiZGY0ZmMtMTUxYy00MzZmLWFlYjktYj=
VlOWI0ZDYwZDIz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeaf1f861" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The Financial Ti=
mes reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Big Four accounting firms have admitted hu=
ndreds of violations of regulations designed to protect the independence of=
 their audit work, following the introduction of new disclosure rules in th=
e US. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PwC said on Monday that it had identified 129 =
breaches of independence rules affecting 74 clients and [Public Company Acc=
ounting Oversight Board] inspectors had found a further one themselves whil=
e inspecting audit work in 2022. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Deloitte said in its audit =
quality report last month that it had told PCAOB inspectors of 129 breaches=
 across 78 clients in 2022 =E2=80=94 affecting approximately 3 per cent of =
its US audits =E2=80=94 and 107 across 53 clients in the 2023 inspection cy=
cle. EY also said it had found independence violations affecting 3 per cent=
 of its audits in 2022.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What kind of violations? Oh:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PwC, Deloitte and EY all said that they had lo=
oked into each violation and concluded there were no cases in which the ind=
ependence of an audit was actually compromised. A person familiar with the =
situation at PwC said one example was the spouse of a staffer holding a cas=
h balance on payments app Venmo while PwC was auditing Venmo=E2=80=99s pare=
nt company PayPal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Deloitte said the most common instances of non=
-compliance were =E2=80=9Crelated to financial relationships and employment=
 relationships of approximately 145,000 professionals monitored=E2=80=9D.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI would characterise them as technica=
l violations,=E2=80=9D said Dennis McGowan, vice-president of the Center fo=
r Audit Quality, which represents large US accounting firms. =E2=80=9CThese=
 firms are big, with a lot of people in them, and they have put in the cont=
rols and systems to track people=E2=80=99s compliance, which is why these a=
re almost always self-reported items.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I submit to you that, if you are the partner o=
n the PayPal audit, the fact that one of your accountants has a spouse who =
has a cash balance on Venmo is much, much, much, much, much, much, much les=
s likely to compromise the independence of your audit than is the fact that=
 you have to talk to PayPal=E2=80=99s employees to do the audit, and you wa=
nt those conversations to be friendly.</p>
