nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about how a ch=
ange in US bank capital rules might affect the market for tax equity financ=
ing, a form of quasi-debt financing in which big banks fund green energy pr=
ojects by, effectively, buying the tax credits that they are expected to ge=
nerate over their lifetimes. The idea is that, to be respected by the Inter=
nal Revenue Service, these deals cannot=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>be just=
=C2=A0<em>buying=C2=A0</em>the tax credit, or lending against it: They have=
 to look like equity investments in the green projects. (=E2=80=9CYou don=
=E2=80=99t go around selling tax credits,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ca=
nd your tax lawyers will get mad if you say that.=E2=80=9D) But to get good=
 capital treatment from bank regulators, these deals cannot=C2=A0<em>really=
 </em>be equity financing: They have to look like safe debt deals. The glor=
y of modern=C2=A0US financial engineering is that banks can build a product=
 that satisfies both of these objectives =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is equity to t=
he IRS but debt to bank regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they did, and it was =
good, and now new bank capital rules might kill it, and the banks are mad.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A bunch of readers emailed, though, to point o=
ut that the problem isn=E2=80=99t that big, because the 2022 Inflation Redu=
ction Act <em>did </em>make it legal to just buy and sell certain green-ene=
rgy tax credits directly. So instead of getting a big bank to do the tax eq=
uity financing song and dance =E2=80=94=C2=A0which currently works, but whi=
ch might not work under proposed new capital rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can j=
ust sell the tax break, for cash up front, to a bank or anyone else who wan=
ts to buy it. Here is an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWtpbmd1bXAuY29tL2VuL2luc2lnaHRzL2Fs=
ZXJ0cy9jbGVhbi1lbmVyZ3ktdGF4LWNyZWRpdC10cmFuc2ZlcmFiaWxpdHktZ3VpZGFuY2UtaXN=
zdWVk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB267684d6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Akin Gump memo</a> on t=
he tax credit transferability guidance.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not necessarily a perfect substitute f=
or tax equity, and the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly9hY29yZS5vcmcvcmVzb3VyY2VzL3RoZS1yaXNrLXByb2=
ZpbGUtb2YtcmVuZXdhYmxlLWVuZXJneS10YXgtZXF1aXR5LWludmVzdG1lbnRzLw/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB2b3f54cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> American Council on Renewable Energy repo=
rt</a> that I quoted yesterday says: =E2=80=9CWhile the IRA provides new ta=
x credit monetization options through transferable tax credits and direct p=
ay, tax equity is expected to remain the most common and preferred option f=
or project developers because it monetizes both the tax credits and other t=
ax benefits, such as tax depreciation.=E2=80=9D Still I suppose the broad c=
onclusion might be that when a financial engineering door is closed, a fina=
ncial engineering window is opened.</p>
