<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMDkvaW1hZ2luYXJ5LWFydC1zZWxsZXItZHJvdmUtYS1oYXJ=
kLWJhcmdhaW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEzMDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG=
1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0d=
WZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f0c103e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked a few times</a> abo=
ut the long-running dispute between art dealer Yves Bouvier and his former =
customer Dmitry Rybolovlev. Basically Bouvier would buy a painting for $126=
 million, tell Rybolovlev =E2=80=9CI think I can get this painting for you =
for $185 million, the sellers want $190 million but I=E2=80=99ll try to tal=
k them down,=E2=80=9D and then he=E2=80=99d sell Rybolovlev the painting fo=
r $184 million. Rybolovlev thought he got a good deal and good service from=
 Bouvier, who was able to talk the sellers down from their asking price. Bu=
t really he got a bad deal and bad service from Bouvier, who=C2=A0<em>was=
=C2=A0</em>the seller, and who took only a little bit off his own enormous =
undisclosed markup.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The question is basically, was Bouvier allowed=
 to do this (as a third-party seller in a sharp-elbowed market), or not (as=
 a trusted advisor in a fiduciary relationship with Rybolovlev). Courts in =
various countries have mostly said it=E2=80=99s fine, but there=E2=80=99s a=
 trial on in New York now in which Rybolovlev is suing Sotheby=E2=80=99s, t=
he auction house, for helping Bouvier inflate his valuations.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For some reason this is a thing? Like, Bouvier=
 would buy a painting at a more-or-less made-up number from someone else, a=
nd then he=E2=80=99d make up a higher number to tell Rybolovlev, and then R=
ybolovlev would pay that higher number or something close to it. But before=
 doing so, I suppose he needed some independent third party to say =E2=80=
=9Coh yes, that number, that=E2=80=99s a good number.=E2=80=9D None of this=
 is real, there are no cash flows, each item is unique and there is no fung=
ible liquid market for it, and the correct value for a=C2=A0<em>da Vinci pa=
inting=C2=A0</em>is surely =E2=80=9Cwhatever the most enthusiastic Russian =
oligarch or Saudi prince will pay for it.=E2=80=9D Any valuation that anyon=
e gave Rybolovlev was necessarily self-referential.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a fun <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2N=
vbnRlbnQvMjU0MTBjMzYtMjMxMi00ZmZjLTk3N2EtM2JkNGY1MzkyYjdl/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB786dbe22" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> Financial Times article</a> about how that case =
is going:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over multiple days of testimony, S=
amuel Valette =E2=80=94 the global head of private sales at Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s who sold many of the works to Bouvier, the Swiss dealer who worked for=
 years with Rybolovlev =E2=80=94 detailed the process by which works, inclu=
ding Leonardo da Vinci=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CSalvator Mundi=E2=80=9D, were pro=
cured for Bouvier, his top client at the time.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Salvator Mundi=E2=80=99s modern price history =
is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A group of art dealers <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53a=
WtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvU2FsdmF0b3JfTXVuZGlfKExlb25hcmRvKQ/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBda65ac07" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> paid $1,175 for it</a>=C2=A0in 2005 at an auctio=
n in New Orleans. They had it restored, and people became convinced it was =
the original by da Vinci.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In 2013,=
 Sotheby=E2=80=99s negotiated a sale between those dealers and Bouvier, =E2=
=80=9Cwho started negotiations with what he described as a =E2=80=98brutall=
y low=E2=80=99 offer of about $47mn. The sellers were hoping for at least $=
100mn.=E2=80=9D Ultimately Bouvier paid =E2=80=9C$68mn, plus a painting by =
Picasso valued at $12mn,=E2=80=9D which I guess adds up to $80 million if y=
ou believe the number on the Picasso.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">=E2=80=9CBouvier would sell the painting to Rybolovlev shortly afterwar=
ds for $127.5mn.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=
=9CFour years later, Rybolovlev resold the work at auction, this time at Ch=
ristie=E2=80=99s, for a record-shattering $450mn,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34176316.282398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudG=
hlZ3VhcmRpYW4uY29tL2FydGFuZGRlc2lnbi8yMDE3L2RlYy8wNy93b3JsZC1yZWNvcmQtZGEtd=
mluY2ktcGFpbnRpbmctdG8tYmUtZXhoaWJpdGVkLWF0LWxvdXZyZS1hYnUtZGhhYmk/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB189462d5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> apparently to Abu Dhabi</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the reasonable range of possible values of =
this painting would run from, say, $1,000 to $450 million. Just, really, pi=
ck a number. And Sotheby=E2=80=99s did:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Emails show how as art valuations soared, marg=
ins of $5mn to $10mn on these =E2=80=9Ctrophy=E2=80=9D artworks felt like r=
ounding errors. Over email in 2015, Valette expressed frustration when a co=
lleague at Sotheby=E2=80=99s pushed back on his request for a higher valuat=
ion for the da Vinci painting two years after the original sale to Bouvier =
was agreed. The colleague said =E2=82=AC95mn was =E2=80=9Cthe most [he] cou=
ld live with=E2=80=9D but Valette told the court he thought =E2=80=9C95 was=
 too precise=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Can awkward number=E2=80=9D, and pushed f=
or =E2=82=AC100mn, or about $110mn.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Valette said he wanted a big, round number. =
=E2=80=9CIn this world, if you=E2=80=99re at =E2=82=AC95mn, you=E2=80=99re =
at =E2=82=AC100mn, =E2=80=9D he said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99m sorry, that=E2=80=99s just correct=
, if you are providing a valuation of that painting to a potential buyer, t=
he correct valuation is just a piece of paper saying =E2=80=9Chow frisky ar=
e you feeling?=E2=80=9D Too much precision really is awkward.</p>
